tool.name: Ensemble_Model

param.name: in_layers
param.dialogReference:
Two or more NetCDF files containing fuzzy belief and disbelief evidence layers generated prior using the Ensemble Sigmoider tool. Requires x, y dimensions and "sigmoid" variable.

Each input must be assigned as either belief or disbelief:

- belief: values closer 1 represent areas you believe your target is highly likely to exist

- disbelief: values closer to 1 represent areas you do not believe your target is highly likely to exist

Note: inputs must be projected in GDA94 Albers (EPSG: 3577).

param.name: out_nc
param.dialogReference:
A NetCDF file containing the ensemble model results. Four variables are contained within the output:

The output NetCDF file containing Ensemble output. This output contains four variables:

- belief: the combination of all belief (i.e. presence) evidence

- disbelief: the combination of all disbelief (i.e. absence) evidence

- plausibility: the combined belief and disbelief evidence showing all possible areas (accurate or not) of the target phenomenon

- interval: areas where the ensemble model was uncertain based on current evidence data

param.name: in_resample
param.dialogReference:
If pixel resolution in input NetCDFs are inconsistent, all NetCDFs must be resampled to either the lowest or highest resolution within the set. Set whether to resample to the lowest (e.g., 30m) or highest (e.g., 1m) resolution found.

Note: it is recommended resampling is done to the lowest resolution.

param.name: in_smooth
param.dialogReference: Smooth input fuzzy evidence layers to reduce noise and improve Ensemble outputs.

param.name: in_win_size
param.dialogReference: If smoothing is requested, set the amount of smoothing based on focal window size. The smoothing value must be an odd number between 3 and 99. Higher values apply more smoothing.

param.name: in_add_result_to_map
param.dialogReference: Whether to visualise the outputs of the tool on the currently active map.

tool.summary:
Performs Dempster-Shafer belief modelling by taking two or more NetCDF file fuzzy evidence layers created prior via the Ensemble Sigmoider tool. Dempster-Shafer performs probability-based ensemble modelling by combing multiple evidence layers into four outputs such as evidence plausibility and uncertainty (i.e., under-sampled areas of the landscape).

See citation: https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/computer-science/dempster-shafer-theory.
